<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="909" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,918,1173]" box="[212,320,918,941]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<heading box="[212,320,918,941]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,320,918,941]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,918,1173]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
With typical characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grandjean" authorityYear="1936" box="[519,653,957,981]" class="Arachnida" family="Galumnidae" genus="Pergalumna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[519,653,957,981]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Pergalumna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; rostrum with small triangular central tooth, lateral carina absent; rostral and lamellar setae thin, finely barbed; interlamellar seta long, thin, finely barbed; sensillus medium long, with finely barbed, slightly dilated head; porose area 
<emphasis box="[435,467,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Aa</emphasis>
large, nearly elongate triangular, its lateral part wide, but medial part narrowed, 
<emphasis box="[479,508,1085,1112]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[498,508,1095,1112]" fontSize="7" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">1</subScript>
</emphasis>
small, round, 
<emphasis box="[680,710,1085,1112]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[700,710,1095,1112]" fontSize="7" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[772,801,1085,1112]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[791,801,1095,1112]" fontSize="7" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
elongate oval, subequal in size; median pore present, consisted of single pore; notogastral lyrifissure 
<emphasis box="[981,1009,1118,1141]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">im</emphasis>
positioned far anterior from seta 
<emphasis box="[426,446,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">lp</emphasis>
; postanal porose area large, elongate oval.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="911" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,1240,1367]" box="[212,372,1240,1263]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<heading box="[212,372,1240,1263]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,372,1240,1263]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Measurements</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,1240,1367]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<typeStatus box="[212,322,1279,1303]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Holotype</typeStatus>
: body length 
<quantity box="[485,575,1279,1304]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.52" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" unit="mm" value="552.0">552 µm</quantity>
, width of notogaster 
<quantity box="[831,921,1279,1304]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" unit="mm" value="400.0">400 µm</quantity>
, length of notogaster 
<quantity box="[212,298,1311,1336]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.64" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" unit="mm" value="464.0">464 µm</quantity>
; 
<typeStatus box="[312,421,1312,1336]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[438,451,1312,1335]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">n</emphasis>
= 2): body length 545–570 (558) µm, width of notogaster 380– 470 (425) µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,1434,1561]" box="[212,339,1434,1457]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<heading box="[212,339,1434,1457]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,339,1434,1457]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,1434,1561]" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<emphasis box="[212,344,1474,1497]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Integument.</emphasis>
Body colour dark brown. Cuticle of body and legs with minute granules; humeral region, posterior part of notogaster and epimeral region with few small tubercles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[212,1172,1603,1692]" lastBlockId="30.[212,1172,168,320]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="911" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">
<emphasis box="[212,341,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Prodorsum.</emphasis>
Rostrum with small triangular central tooth, which is easily seen in dorsofrontal view, lateral carina absent (
<figureCitation box="[683,898,1635,1659]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="22.[212,279,1433,1455]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,168,1400]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[213,1170,168,1401]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figure 11. Morphological characters of different species. (A––D) Galumna iranensis Mahunka et Akrami, 2001. (A) Lateral view of proterosoma (arrow indicates dorsosejugal porose area Ad); (B) dorsal view of prodorsum (arrow indicates central carina of rostrum); (C) lateral part of notogaster; (D) lateral view of sensillus. (E–H) Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (E) Posterior view of notogaster showing porose areas A3 and Ap; (F) porose area Aa; (G) posterior part of notogaster; (H) pteromorph." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006697/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="909">Figure 11B and C</figureCitation>
). Rostral seta thin, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.35" metricValueMax="7.6" metricValueMin="7.1" pageId="28" pageNumber="909" unit="mm" value="73.5" valueMax="76.0" valueMin="71.0">71– 76 µm</quantity>
long, finely barbed, inserted ventrally and clearly visible in dorsofrontal view. Lamellar seta thin, 
<quantity box="[437,549,168,193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="8.8" metricValueMin="8.2" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="85.0" valueMax="88.0" valueMin="82.0">82–88 µm</quantity>
long, finely barbed. Interlamellar seta thin, 
<quantity box="[1060,1172,168,193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.95" metricValueMax="9.3" metricValueMin="8.6" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="89.5" valueMax="93.0" valueMin="86.0">86–93 µm</quantity>
long, finely barbed. Sensillus 
<quantity box="[543,653,200,225]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.4" metricValueMax="8.6" metricValueMin="8.2" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="84.0" valueMax="86.0" valueMin="82.0">82–86 µm</quantity>
long, with finely barbed, slightly dilated head (one specimen showed finely barbed setiform sensillus). Lamellar and sublamellar lines well developed (
<figureCitation box="[461,678,264,288]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figure 14A and B</figureCitation>
). Dorsosejugal porose area large, elongate oval, located posterolaterad of seta 
<emphasis box="[621,641,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">in</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="910" startId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" targetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" targetPageId="29">
<paragraph blockId="29.[144,1104,1496,1576]" pageId="29" pageNumber="910">
Figure 14. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bayartogtokh &amp; Akrami, 2014" authorityName="Bayartogtokh &amp; Akrami" authorityYear="2014" box="[260,556,1496,1517]" class="Arachnida" family="Galumnidae" genus="Pergalumna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="910" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microtuberculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[260,556,1496,1517]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="910">Pergalumna microtuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[563,644,1496,1517]" pageId="29" pageNumber="910" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,359,543]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<emphasis box="[212,342,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Notogaster.</emphasis>
Notogaster widened posteriorly, dorsosejugal furrow well developed. Pteromorph nearly smooth, with small granules. Notogastral setae vestigial, their alveoli well discernable. Porose area 
<emphasis box="[638,670,424,447]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Aa</emphasis>
large, nearly elongate triangular, its lateral part widened, but medial part narrowed; 
<emphasis box="[679,708,456,482]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[698,708,465,482]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">1</subScript>
</emphasis>
round, 
<emphasis box="[799,828,456,482]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[818,828,465,482]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[886,915,456,482]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[905,915,465,482]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
elongate oval; median pore present, consisting of single pore. Lyrifissures 
<emphasis box="[792,812,488,511]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">ia</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[827,855,488,511]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">im</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[870,890,487,511]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">ih</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[906,926,488,511]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">ip</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[942,972,488,511]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">ips</emphasis>
and opisthonotal gland opening well developed (
<figureCitation box="[565,739,519,543]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="22.[212,279,1433,1455]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,168,1400]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[213,1170,168,1401]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figure 11. Morphological characters of different species. (A––D) Galumna iranensis Mahunka et Akrami, 2001. (A) Lateral view of proterosoma (arrow indicates dorsosejugal porose area Ad); (B) dorsal view of prodorsum (arrow indicates central carina of rostrum); (C) lateral part of notogaster; (D) lateral view of sensillus. (E–H) Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (E) Posterior view of notogaster showing porose areas A3 and Ap; (F) porose area Aa; (G) posterior part of notogaster; (H) pteromorph." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006697/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figures 11E–H</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[798,828,519,543]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,583,766]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<emphasis box="[212,358,583,607]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krefft" authorityYear="1871" box="[212,354,583,607]" class="Chromadorea" family="Gnathostomatidae" genus="Gnathosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">Gnathosoma</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Subcapitulum longer than wide, with few microtubercles; hypostomal setae 
<emphasis box="[274,287,615,638]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">a</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[301,321,615,638]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">m</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[378,391,615,639]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">h</emphasis>
<quantity box="[398,494,615,639]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="9.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="8.0">8–11 µm</quantity>
long, smooth (
<figureCitation box="[664,795,615,639]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figure 14D</figureCitation>
). Palp typical for family, all setae except on tarsus finely barbed, formula of setation: 0-2-1-3-10 including solenidion 
<emphasis box="[1153,1172,647,671]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">ω</emphasis>
on tarsus. Chelicera with few heavily sclerotized blunt teeth on fixed and movable digits; setae 
<emphasis box="[350,388,710,734]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">cha</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[447,485,710,734]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">chb</emphasis>
long, barbed; Trägårdh’ s organ well developed, its proximal part well discernable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,806,926]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<emphasis box="[212,401,806,830]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Epimeral region.</emphasis>
With large granules and longitudinal striations; apodemes 
<emphasis box="[1104,1165,806,830]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">apo.1</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[212,272,838,862]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">apo.2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[290,355,839,862]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">apo.sj</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[372,433,838,862]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">apo.3</emphasis>
, circumpedal carina and discidium well developed. Six pairs of short epimeral setae of 
<quantity box="[533,658,870,894]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="12.0">12–18 µm</quantity>
length observed, setal formula: 2-0-2-2 (
<figureCitation box="[220,354,902,926]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figure 14D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,965,1117]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<emphasis box="[212,425,965,989]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Ano-genital region.</emphasis>
Anal aperture 
<quantity box="[599,683,965,990]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="110.0">110 µm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[755,839,965,990]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.31" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="131.0">131 µm</quantity>
wide; genital aperture 
<quantity box="[1101,1172,966,990]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.7" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="77.0">77 µm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[276,346,997,1022]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.6" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="86.0">86 µm</quantity>
wide for 
<typeStatus box="[454,556,997,1021]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">holotype</typeStatus>
. Genital and aggenital setae well developed, 
<quantity box="[1062,1172,997,1022]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="14.0">14–19 µm</quantity>
long, thin, smooth; anal and adanal setae vestigial; adanal lyrifissure situated in paranal position, at level little posterior to seta 
<emphasis box="[773,809,1061,1088]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
ad 
<subScript attach="left" box="[799,809,1071,1088]" fontSize="7" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">3</subScript>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[829,964,1061,1085]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figure 14D</figureCitation>
). Postanal porose area large, elongate oval, narrowed bilaterally (
<figureCitation box="[755,885,1093,1117]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="29.[144,211,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[145,1102,168,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 14. Pergalumna microtuberculata sp. nov. (A) Dorsal view of idiosoma; (B) dorsofrontal view of prodorsum, partial; (C) ventral view of idiosoma; (D) posterior view of notogaster, partial." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006703/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Figure 14E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,1157,1276]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">
<emphasis box="[212,272,1158,1181]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Legs.</emphasis>
Structure and setation of legs typical for family as shown in the description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bayartogtokh &amp; Akrami, 2014" authorityName="Bayartogtokh &amp; Akrami" authorityYear="2014" box="[212,501,1189,1213]" class="Arachnida" family="Galumnidae" genus="Allogalumna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentirostrata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[212,501,1189,1213]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="911">Allogalumna dentirostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[508,597,1189,1212]" pageId="30" pageNumber="911" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Formula of setation, including famulus: I (1-4-3-4- 20), II (1-4-3-4-15), III (1-2-1-3-15), IV (1-2-2-3-12), formula of solenidia I (1-2-2), II (1-1-2), III (1-1-0), IV (0-1-0).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
